{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16812"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.07,0.15,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67053"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9503"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52508"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12274"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67053"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the early pregnancy unit with six weeks of amenorrhoea and two days of painless vaginal bleeding. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has had one previous uncomplicated pregnancy resulting in a term vaginal delivery three years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Speculum examination reveals a closed cervical os with minimal bleeding and barrel-shaped cervical enlargement. Serum beta human chorionic gonadotropin is 8,500 IU/L (\u0026gt;5 indicates pregnancy). Transvaginal ultrasound reveals an empty uterine cavity, closed internal os, and a gestational sac with fetal pole below the level of the internal os. The gestational sac position does not change with gentle probe pressure (\u0027negative sliding sign\u0027).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inevitable miscarriage","Interstitial ectopic pregnancy","Incomplete miscarriage","Low implantation pregnancy","Cervical ectopic pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with early pregnancy bleeding, and the ultrasound findings are characteristic of a cervical ectopic pregnancy. The key diagnostic features include an empty uterine cavity, closed internal os, gestational sac implanted below the level of the internal os, and barrel-shaped cervical enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when implantation takes place in the endocervical canal. The absence of the \u0027sliding organ sign\u0027 (where the gestational sac moves when gentle pressure is applied with the transvaginal probe) helps distinguish it from a miscarriage in transit. The presence of cardiac activity, when seen, confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E would show products of conception in the process of passing through a dilated internal cervical os. In this case, the internal os is closed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterstitial ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the proximal portion of the fallopian tube as it enters the uterine wall. On ultrasound, it would appear as an eccentric gestational sac surrounded by a thin rim of myometrium in the cornual region of the uterus, not in the cervical canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincomplete miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows irregular heterogeneous tissue within the uterine cavity or cervical canal, which would slide with gentle probe pressure, unlike the fixed position seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elow implantation pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E would show a gestational sac in the lower uterine segment, above the internal os, rather than below it in the cervical canal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical ectopic pregnancy shows a gestational sac below the internal cervical os on transvaginal ultrasound.","The \u0027sliding organ sign\u0027 is absent in cervical ectopic pregnancy, distinguishing it from a miscarriage in transit.","Empty uterine cavity with closed internal os and barrel-shaped cervical enlargement are key ultrasound features of cervical ectopic pregnancy."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy (Green-top Guideline No. 21). BJOG. 2016;123(13):e15\u2013e55. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1111/1471-0528.14189"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52508"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52508"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T12:31:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T12:32:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id